metadata.name: Heavy Light #19
metadata.description:
This is an experiment in spaces lit by falling particles of light.

Each particle draws a thin trace as it falls and changes its colour whenever it reflects from a wall or an obstacle. 

The piece takes some time to fully render. After the signature appears on the bottom of the picture, you are free to hit 's' to save a high resolution PNG for printing and seeing the finer details.

The work features 5 different canvas sizes and 8 palettes.

metadata.name: Pebbles & Dots #166
metadata.description:
The Pebbles & Dots project echoes the simple pleasures of our childhood.

Picking up pebbles or other small objects in order to fit them together is one of those simple and childish pleasures for which we gradually lose interest as we age.

Through this project, I hope to give you back some interest in these little pleasures too quickly forgotten.

You will love the variations and features!!!
* Pebbles_Size
* Pebbles_Shape
* Pebbles_Spacing
* Tidiness
* Dark_Light_Ratio
* Contour
* Shadow
* Inverted
* Paper_Color
* ??? (Surprise)

Artist: Estienne
Dec 2021

metadata.name: Phantoms #239
metadata.description:
Phantoms is a series of hazy memories of distant places. Some tranquil, others sinister, each scene is as much defined by what is revealed as by what remains unseen.

In this collection I aim to juxtapose hard and soft. Blocky shapes form the core of the compositions. Upon these surfaces, soft textures appear to flow and drip over the sides. Varying levels of opacity, lighting, and fog effects further soften the scenes to create an atmospheric, dream-like quality. By remaining semi-abstract, each of the color palettes are given the space to influence the mood dramatically.

metadata.name: Particularization #69
metadata.description:
“Particularization” is the seventh collection released as a part of NeoMent's "Abandoned Reality" series.

All concepts can be viewed from different levels. You can focus on the details, leaving out the generalized result but understanding the finer points. Or you could emphasize the concept as a whole, comprehending it well overall but missing out on the specifics. It's impossible to choose both, you have to figure out which approach works best for each scenario.
